&nbsp; William Ruto is the current Deputy President of the republic of Kenya, holding office since his election into the new office in the 2013 general election. Ruto, aged 50, holds a Master&rsquo;s of Science in Environmental Science from the University of Nairobi. Ruto&rsquo;s debut in politics began in 1992, where he served as the organizing secretary for Youth for KANU, a movement that had pledged to back up retired president Daniel Moi in his presidential bid in the 1992 election. Being a close ally to Moi, Ruto bid for a parliamentary seat of his Eldoret North Constituency clinched him the seat in 1997. Consequently, he was appointed as Assistant Minister to the Office of the President in 1998. Ruto was then promoted to Minister for Home Affairs in 2002 that saw his succeeding appointment in the ministries of Agriculture and Higher Education. Ruto launched his first appeal for a presidential contender in 2006, announcing he would face the ballot in the 2007 general election on an Orange Democratic Movement (ODM) party ticket. He however lost his bid at the nominations poll, coming third after ODM leader Raila Odinga and Musalia Mudavadi. His loss however saw him garner support behind Raila Odinga. In 2013, William Ruto became the presidential running mate to Uhuru Kenyatta forming an alliance under his United Republican Party (URP) party. ALSO READ: Lottery winner now bags Jubilee Party nominations ticket William Ruto currently seeks a second term as Deputy President, by being President Uhuru Kenyatta&rsquo;s running mate in the 2017 August through the&nbsp;Jubilee ticket. &nbsp;